ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Putting them all together, what were your grades like last year?
Notes: 1=Mostly Fs; 1.75= Mostly Ds; 2.5=Mostly Cs; 3.25=Mostly Bs; 4=Mostly As

ElementDescription: In my school, students have lots of chances to help decide things like class activities and rules.
I get along well with my teachers
My teacher(s) notices when I am doing a good job and lets me know about it
There are lots of chances for students in my school to get involved in sports, clubs, or other school activities outside of class.

The school lets my parents know when I have done something well.
I like school because I do well in class.
I feel I'm just as smart as other kids my age.

SRPF total score
My neighborhood is safe from crime.
Notes: 1 = Strongly Disagree; 2 = Disagree; 3 = Neutral (neither agree nor disagree); 4 = Agree; 5 = Strongly Agree

ElementDescription: My caregiver smiles at me very often.
Notes: 1 = Not like him/her; 2 = Somewhat like him/her; 3 = A lot like him/her

ElementDescription: My caregiver believes in showing his/her love for me.
Notes: 1 = Not like him/her; 2 = Somewhat like him/her; 3 = A lot like him/her

ElementDescription: How often do your parents/guardians know where you are?
Notes: 1 = Never; 2 = Almost Never; 3 = Sometimes; 4 = Often; 5 = Always or Almost Always

ElementDescription: How often do your parents know who you are with when you are not at school and away from home?
Notes: 1 = Never; 2 = Almost Never; 3 = Sometimes; 4 = Often; 5 = Always or Almost Always

ElementDescription: I get along with my teachers.
Notes: 1 = NO! (If you think the statement is definitely not true for you); 2 = No (If you think the statement is mostly not true for you); 3 = Yes (If you think the statement is mostly true for you); 4 = YES! (If you think the statement is definitely true for you)

ElementDescription: I feel safe at my school.
Notes: 1 = NO! (If you think the statement is definitely not true for you); 2 = No (If you think the statement is mostly not true for you); 3 = Yes (If you think the statement is mostly true for you); 4 = YES! (If you think the statement is definitely true for you)
